figures.alternate_text: Sagittal CT scan of the human neck showing anatomical structures. The image highlights the airway and cervical spine with three labeled sections: 1, 2, and 3. Dashed lines indicate specific anatomical levels. The scan provides a detailed view of the soft tissues and vertebrae.

Diagram of the human larynx showing labeled parts: Aryepiglottic Fold, Vestibule, Vestibular Fold, Ventricle, Vocal Fold, and Subglottic Space. Arrows point to each part, illustrating their positions and relationships within the laryngeal structure.

figures.alternate_text: Diagram of the human larynx showing labeled parts: Aryepiglottic Fold, Vestibule, Vestibular Fold, Ventricle, Vocal Fold, and Subglottic Space. Arrows point to each part, illustrating their positions and relationships within the laryngeal structure.

CT scan images of the human larynx in axial view, labeled with anatomical features. Panel (a) shows the valleculla, epiglottis, and vestibule. Panel (b) highlights the pyriform sinus and aryepiglottic folds. Panel (c) identifies the true vocal cords (VC), glottis, and cricoarytenoid joint. Panel (d) marks the false vocal cord. Panel (e) indicates the cricoid cartilage. Each image includes a scale bar of 120 mm.

Diagram of the human trachea and bronchial tree, showing the trachea branching into bronchi. The image includes labels for the level of the manubriosternal joint (sternal angle) and the level of the xiphisternal joint. The vertebra labeled as T.V.10 is also indicated. The diagram highlights anatomical relationships in the thoracic region.

Diagram of the bronchial tree, illustrating the branching structure of the main bronchi, lobar bronchi, and segmental bronchi. The left and right bronchi are color-coded: main bronchi in orange, lobar bronchi in blue, and segmental bronchi in pink. Labels indicate specific bronchial segments, such as 'Apical,' 'Posterior,' 'Anterior,' and 'Lingular.' A legend explains the color coding and divisions, including upper and lower parts of the right main bronchus and upper and lower divisions of the left upper lobe bronchus.

Part figure a: Three-panel image showing endoscopic and CT scan views of the bronchial passages. Panel (a) displays an endoscopic view of a bronchial tube on the left and a corresponding CT scan of the chest on the right, with a scale indicating 200 mm. Panel (b) shows another endoscopic view with a different angle or lighting, alongside a similar CT scan. Panel (c) presents a third endoscopic view, again paired with a CT scan. Each CT scan highlights the bronchial structures within the chest cavity., Part figure b: A composite image showing endoscopic and CT scan views of the respiratory system. The left column displays endoscopic images of the bronchial passages, highlighting the internal structure and texture. The right column features corresponding CT scans of the chest, illustrating the cross-sectional view of the lungs and airways. Each CT image includes a scale bar indicating 200 mm. The images are labeled with letters 'd' and 'e' in the top left corners of the respective rows.
